### Detailed Findings & Remediation

---

#### 🔴 Finding 1 — No Authentication on `/users` (A01 Broken Access Control)

**Current code:**
```js
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob', email: 'bob@example.com' },
  ]);
});
```

Any unauthenticated caller can enumerate all users and their PII. Even with a small dataset today, this pattern is dangerous as the app scales.

**Recommendation — add a JWT auth middleware:**
```js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const auth = req.headers['authorization'];
  if (!auth?.startsWith('Bearer ')) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Missing or malformed token' });
  }
  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(auth.slice(7), process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid or expired token' });
  }
}

// Apply to protected routes
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { ... });
```

---

#### 🔴 Finding 2 — No HTTPS Enforcement (A02 Cryptographic Failures)

The server listens on plain HTTP. All data — including any future auth tokens — travels unencrypted.

**Recommendation:**
```js
// In production, terminate TLS at the load balancer/reverse proxy (nginx, ALB).
// In the app, redirect HTTP → HTTPS:
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  if (process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production' && req.headers['x-forwarded-proto'] !== 'https') {
    return res.redirect(301, `https://${req.hostname}${req.originalUrl}`);
  }
  next();
});
```

---

#### 🟠 Finding 3 — Missing Security Headers (A05 Security Misconfiguration)

No HTTP security headers are set. This exposes users to clickjacking, MIME-sniffing, and other browser-based attacks.

**Recommendation — add `helmet`:**
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // Sets X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, HSTS, CSP, etc.
```

Install: `npm install helmet`

---

#### 🟠 Finding 4 — No CORS Policy (A05 Security Misconfiguration)

Without an explicit CORS policy, browsers may apply overly permissive defaults (or the app may fail to serve legitimate cross-origin clients correctly).

**Recommendation:**
```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({
  origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS?.split(',') ?? [],
  methods: ['GET', 'POST', 'PUT', 'DELETE'],
  allowedHeaders: ['Authorization', 'Content-Type'],
  credentials: true,
}));
```

---

#### 🟠 Finding 5 — No Rate Limiting (A07 Identification and Authentication Failures)

There is no throttling on any endpoint. The `/users` route (or a future `/login` route) can be scraped or brute-forced without limit.

**Recommendation:**
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // max 100 requests per window per IP
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
  message: { error: 'Too many requests, please try again later.' },
});

app.use(limiter); // Apply globally, or per-route for tighter control
```

Install: `npm install express-rate-limit`

---

#### 🟡 Finding 6 — PII Exposed Without Authorization (A04 Insecure Design)

Email addresses are PII. Even when authentication is added (Finding 1), consider whether callers actually need full email addresses returned, or whether a scoped/redacted view is more appropriate for most use cases.

**Recommendation:** Apply the principle of least privilege at the data layer:
```js
// Return only what the caller needs
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Only admins get emails; others get a public profile
  const isAdmin = req.user?.role === 'admin';
  const users = fetchUsers(); // from DB
  res.json(users.map(u => ({
    id: u.id,
    name: u.name,
    ...(isAdmin ? { email: u.email } : {}),
  })));
});
```

---

#### 🟡 Finding 7 — No Logging or Error Handling (A09 Security Logging and Monitoring Failures)

There is no request logging and no global error handler. Unhandled errors will expose raw Express stack traces to callers in development mode, and security events will go undetected in production.

**Recommendation:**
```js
const morgan = require('morgan');

// Request logging
app.use(morgan('combined')); // Use a structured logger (pino, winston) in production

// Global error handler (must be last middleware)
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error({ err, path: req.path, method: req.method }); // Log to your SIEM
  res.status(err.status ?? 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
      ? 'Internal server error'   // Never leak stack traces
      : err.message,
  });
});
```

---

#### 🟡 Finding 8 — Hardcoded Port (A05 Security Misconfiguration)

Port `3000` is hardcoded. This makes it harder to deploy securely across environments and can cause conflicts.

**Recommendation:**
```js
const PORT = parseInt(process.env.PORT ?? '3000', 10);
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

